<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="180" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,821,2034]" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,821,846]" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. The shape of the mandible is diagnostic for this species, not only within the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[1410,1429,822,845]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">C</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[160,331,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Rhinocoelioxys</emphasis>
) but also among all species of 
<taxonomicName box="[728,838,857,882]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Coelioxys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[728,838,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Coelioxys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to us. The mandible is strongly flattened dorsoventrally and covered with a fringe of pale hairs laterally and a fringe of dark hairs subapically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
